{{Infobox | title = Autumn in New England | image = {{image array|perrow=2|width=135|height=100. | image1 = Barndoor_Hills_original.JPG | caption1 = [[Barndoor Hills]], [[Connecticut]] | image2 = Lemonresized50.jpg | caption2 = [[Lemon Stream]], [[Maine]] | image3 = Autumn Massachusetts 1.jpg | caption3 = [[Connecticut River]], [[Massachusetts]] | image4 = New_hampshire_colors.jpg | caption4 = [[New Hampshire]] | image5 = Blackstone-River-Bikeway.jpg | caption5 = [[Blackstone River Bikeway]], [[Rhode Island]] | image6 = Fall_foliage_at_Missisquoi_National_Wildlife_Refuge_(9965485026).jpg | caption6 = [[Missisquoi National Wildlife Refuge]], [[Vermont]] }} | decat = yes <!-- infobox template used solely for images --> }} The '''autumn in New England''' marks the transition from [[summer]] to [[winter]] in [[New England]], [[United States]]. The [[autumn]] color of trees in New England has been said to be some of the most brilliant color in the United States. Travelers from many areas of the USA and even Europe flock to [[Vermont]], [[New Hampshire]], [[Maine]], and parts of [[Massachusetts]] to see the colors each fall. <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discovernewengland.org/seasons/fall/|title=New England Fall Foliage|publisher=Discover New England|accessdate=16 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140922175159/http://www.discovernewengland.org/seasons/fall/|archive-date=2014-09-22|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2012/09/21/travel/fall-leaf-peeping-autumn/|title=When autumn leaves fall|publisher=CNN|date=12 October 2012|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref> [[Hiking]] has become popular among the tourists, and several areas offer guided tours.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://discovernewengland.org/things-do/walking-hiking|title=Walking & Hiking|publisher=Discover New England|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref>
The combination of the natural rugged landscape with the rural and small town villages has made several areas in New England iconic in terms of fall color photography. The numerous [[barn]]s, [[church building]]s, [[farmhouse]]s, and [[village]]s combined with the bright oranges, reds, and yellows makes for iconic foliage photographs. <ref name="New England in the Fall">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/activityandadventure/9590099/New-England-in-the-Fall-Trip-of-a-Lifetime.html|title=New England in the Fall: Trip of a Lifetime|publisher=Telegraph|author=Paul Wade and Kathy Arnol|date=16 September 2014|accessdate=26 September 2015}}</ref>
==Natural change== Across most of New England, by mid September the days are still warm, but the nights have become cool, and this is the process that begins the colorful change in trees that occur each fall. Trees sense the lowering of the solar angle and reduced hours of daylight, this starts the process of the [[chlorophyll]] breaking down, the green color disappears, and the yellow to orange colors become visible. This change is most acute in [[sugar maple]] trees. This change in color starts in far Northern New England in northern Maine and the higher elevations of Vermont and New Hampshire in mid September, reaching central New England areas of southern Vermont, southern New Hampshire, and Massachusetts by early October. By mid October the color peak reaches northern Rhode Island and northern Connecticut.
As one reaches southern Connecticut southward toward into New Jersey and points south, the number of sugar maple trees declines as the climate changes to a more [[temperate zone]] and [[oak]]s become more dominant, thus there are less bright colors.<ref name="New England in the Fall"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/travel/destinations/north-america/united-states/articles/New-England-in-the-Fall-Trip-of-a-Lifetime/|title=Everything you need to know about visiting New England in the Fall|publisher=Telegraph|language=English|author=Paul Wade and Kathy Arnold|date=4 October 2016|accessdate=29 August 2017}}</ref>
==In popular culture== Autumn in New England has also become a popular theme in American popular culture, with many fictional stories being set in autumntime New England.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hellogiggles.com/movies-autumn-supporting-character|title=Fall in Love|publisher=Hellogiggles|author=Andrea Greb|date=7 September 2014|accessdate=16 September 2014}}</ref>
