{{good article}}
[[File:TD2 aug 12 2009 1335Z.jpg|thumb|right|[[Tropical Storm Ana (2009)]] with its small CDO]]
The '''central dense overcast''', or '''CDO''', of a [[tropical cyclone]] or strong [[subtropical cyclone]] is the large central area of [[thunderstorm]]s surrounding its circulation center, caused by the formation of its eyewall.  It can be round, angular, oval, or irregular in shape.  This feature shows up in tropical cyclones of tropical storm or hurricane strength.  How far the center is embedded within the CDO, and the temperature difference between the cloud tops within the CDO and the cyclone's eye, can help determine a tropical cyclone's intensity.  Locating the center within the CDO can be a problem for strong tropical storms and with systems of minimal hurricane strength as its location can be obscured by the CDO's high cloud canopy.  This center location problem can be resolved through the use of microwave satellite imagery.

After a [[cyclone]] reaches hurricane intensity, an [[eye (cyclone)|eye]] appears at the center of the CDO, defining its center of [[low pressure area|low pressure]] and its cyclonic wind field.  Tropical cyclones with changing intensity have more lightning within their CDO than [[steady state]] storms.  Tracking cloud features within the CDO, using frequently updated [[satellite imagery]], can also be used to determine its intensity.  The highest [[maximum sustained wind]]s within a tropical cyclone, as well as its heaviest rainfall, are usually located under the coldest cloud tops in the CDO.

==Characteristics==
[[File:Winston 2016-02-12 1200Z.png|thumb|right|Southern hemisphere tropical [[cyclone Winston]] with a large CDO surrounding its eye]]
It is a large region of thunderstorms surrounding the center of stronger tropical and subtropical cyclones which shows up brightly (with cold cloud tops) on [[satellite imagery]].<ref name="CDO AMS">{{cite web|date=June 2000|author=American Meteorological Society|author-link=American Meteorological Society|url=http://amsglossary.allenpress.com/glossary/browse?s=c&p=19|title=AMS Glossary: C|work=Glossary of Meteorology|accessdate=2006-12-14|publisher=[[Allen Press]]}}</ref><ref name="FAQ CDO">{{cite web | author=Landsea, Chris | title=What is a "CDO"? | date=2005-10-19 | publisher=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]] | accessdate=2006-06-14 | url = http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/tcfaqHED.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=A Satellite Classification Technique For Subtropical Cyclones|page=9|author1=Hebert, Paul H.  |author2=Kenneth O. Poteat|date=July 1975|publisher=[[National Weather Service]] Southern Region Headquarters}}</ref>  The CDO forms due to the development of an eyewall within a tropical cyclone.<ref>{{cite book|title=Hurricanes of the North Atlantic: Climate and Society|page=3|author1=Elsner, James B.  |author2=A. Birol Kara|ISBN=978-0195125085|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=1999-06-10}}</ref>  Its shape can be round, oval, angular, or irregular.<ref name="Vern">{{cite journal|author=Dvorak, Vernon F.|title=A Technique For the Analysis and Forecasting of Tropical Cyclone Intensities From Satellite Pictures|pages=5–8|date=February 1973|publisher=[[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]]}}</ref>  Its development can be preceded by a narrow, dense, C-shaped [[Rainband|convective band]].  Early in its development, the CDO is often angular or oval in shape, which rounds out, increases in size, and appears more smooth as a tropical cyclone intensifies.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Monthly Weather Review|page=422|volume=103|title=Tropical Cyclone Intensity Analysis and Forecasting From Satellite Imagery|author=Dvorak, Vernon F.|date=May 1975|doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1975)103<0420:tciaaf>2.0.co;2|bibcode = 1975MWRv..103..420D }}</ref>  Rounder CDO shapes occur in environments with low levels of vertical [[wind shear]].<ref name="FAQ CDO"/>

The strongest winds within [[tropical cyclone]]s tend to be located under the deepest [[convection]] within the CDO, which is seen on satellite imagery as the coldest cloud tops.<ref name="HSU"/>   The [[radius of maximum wind]] is usually collocated with the coldest cloud tops within the CDO,<ref name="HSU">{{cite web|author1=Hsu, S. A.|author2=Adele Babin|url=http://www.nwas.org/ej/hsu/hsu_babin_2005.pdf|title=Estimating the Radius of Maximum Winds Via Satellite During Hurricane Lili (2002) Over the Gulf of Mexico|accessdate=2007-03-18|date=February 2005|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120206133851/http://www.nwas.org/ej/hsu/hsu_babin_2005.pdf|archivedate=2012-02-06|df=}}</ref> which is also the area where a tropical cyclone's rainfall reaches its maximum intensity.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.mri-jma.go.jp/Publish/Technical/DATA/VOL_14/14_abs.pdf|title=The Study on the Changes of the Three-dimensional Structure and the Movement Speed of the Typhoon through its Life Time|author=Muramatsu, Teruo|journal=Tech. Rep. Meteorol. Res. Inst. Number 14|year=1985|page=3|accessdate=2009-11-20}}</ref>  For mature tropical cyclones that are steady state, the CDO contains nearly no [[lightning]] activity, though lightning is more common within weaker tropical cyclones and for systems fluctuating in intensity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vaisala.com/Vaisala%20Documents/Scientific%20papers/Long%20range%20lightning%20nowcasting%20applications%20for%20meteorology.pdf|title=Long Range Lightning Nowcasting Applications For Meteorology|author=Demetriades, Nicholas W.S.|author2=Martin J. Murphy|author3=Ronald L. Holle|last-author-amp=yes|publisher=Vaisala|date=2005-06-22|accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref>

==Eye==
{{Main article|Eye (cyclone)}}
The eye is a region of mostly calm [[weather]] at the center of the CDO of strong [[tropical cyclone]]s.  The eye of a [[storm]] is a roughly circular area, typically 30–65&nbsp;km (20–40&nbsp;miles) in [[diameter]]. It is surrounded by the eyewall, a ring of towering [[thunderstorm]]s surrounding its center of circulation.  The cyclone's lowest [[barometric pressure]] occurs in the eye, and can be as much as 15% lower than the [[atmospheric pressure]] outside the storm.<ref name="FAQ eye">{{cite web | author=Landsea, Chris | author-link=Chris Landsea | author2=Sim Aberson | last-author-amp=yes | title=What is the "eye"? | date=2004-08-13 | publisher=[[Atlantic Oceanographic and Meteorological Laboratory]] | accessdate=2006-06-14 | url = http://www.aoml.noaa.gov/hrd/tcfaq/A11.html}}</ref>  In weaker tropical cyclones, the eye is less well-defined, and can be covered by high cloudiness caused by [[cirrus cloud]] outflow from the surrounding central dense overcast.<ref name="FAQ eye"/>
{{clear}}

==Use as a tropical cyclone strength indicator==
[[File:Dvorak1984DevelopmentalPatterns.png|thumb|right|Common developmental patterns seen during tropical cyclone development, and their Dvorak-assigned intensities]]
{{See also|Dvorak technique}}
Within the Dvorak satellite strength estimate for tropical cyclones, there are several [[Pattern recognition|visual patterns]] that a cyclone may take on which define the upper and lower bounds on its intensity.  The central dense overcast (CDO) pattern is one of those patterns.  The central dense overcast utilizes the size of the CDO.  The CDO pattern intensities start at T2.5, equivalent to minimal tropical storm intensity, {{convert|40|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}.  The shape of the central dense overcast is also considered.  The farther the center is tucked into the CDO, the stronger it is deemed.<ref name="Vern"/>  Banding features can be utilized to objectively determine the tropical cyclone's center, using a ten degree [[logarithmic spiral]].<ref name="evolution">{{cite journal|url=http://www.nhc.noaa.gov/pdf/06velden.pdf|title=The Dvorak Tropical Cyclone Intensity Estimation Technique: A Satellite-Based Method That Has Endured For Over 30 Years|author=Velden, Christopher|author2=Bruce Harper|author3=Frank Wells|author4=John L. Beven II|author5= Ray Zehr|author6=Timothy Olander|author7=Max Mayfield|author8=Charles “Chip” Guard|author9=Mark Lander|author10=Roger Edson|author11=Lixion Avila|author12=Andrew Burton|author13=Mike Turk|author14=Akihiro Kikuchi|author15=Adam Christian|author16=Philippe Caroff|author17= Paul McCrone|last-author-amp=yes|date=September 2006|pages=1195–1214|doi=10.1175/bams-87-9-1195 |journal=Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society|accessdate=2012-09-26|bibcode = 2006BAMS...87.1195V }}</ref>  Using the 85–92&nbsp;GHz channels of polar-orbiting microwave satellite imagery can definitively locate the center within the CDO.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Objectively Determining the Rotational Center of Tropical Cyclones in Passive Microwave Satellite Imagery|author1=Wimmers, Anthony J.  |author2=Christopher S. Velden|date=September 2012|volume=49|number=9|publisher=[[American Meteorological Society]]|journal=Journal of Applied Meteorology and Climatology|pages=2013–2034|doi=10.1175/2010jamc2490.1|bibcode = 2010JApMC..49.2013W }}</ref>

Tropical cyclones with maximum sustained winds between {{convert|65|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} and {{convert|100|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} can have their center of circulations obscured by cloudiness within visible and infrared satellite imagery, which makes diagnosis of their intensity a challenge.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:TNjsYx3-4tYJ:https://ams.confex.com/ams/30Hurricane/webprogram/Manuscript/Paper205619/hurrconf_2012_archer_extabs.pdf+Objectively+Determining+the+Rotational+Center+of+Tropical+Cyclones+in+Passive+Microwave+Satellite+Imagery+Anthony+J.+Wimmers+and+Christopher+S.+Velden&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEEShshgH1vysQyzdH8CmUQ2cUchwb6JJdg8q2-vIiIJ8uf5nFrmjAtTXCMD2PFrFah5R6Hl5q9A3x1-gV5iiLUzeVQbXO0D35UokP9lPv3wG6KVCjTOQp8zDmToJZzaKoiIXCEdP4&sig=AHIEtbTlbbUiMfUOQ_0o0lCPuM4jkc47bw|title=Advances in Objective Tropical Cyclone Center Fixing Using Multispectral Satellite Imagery|author1=Wimmers, Anthony  |author2=Chistopher Velden|year=2012|accessdate=2012-08-12|publisher=American Meteorological Society}}</ref>  Winds within tropical cyclones can also be estimated by tracking features within the CDO using rapid scan [[Weather satellite#Geostationary|geostationary satellite imagery]], whose pictures are taken minutes apart rather than every half-hour.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Rogers, Edward|author2=R. Cecil Gentry|author3=William Shenk|author4=Vincent Oliver|last-author-amp=yes|title=The Benefits of Using Short-Interval Satellite Images To Derive Winds For Tropical Cyclones|journal=Monthly Weather Review|publisher=American Meteorological Society|volume=107|page=575|date=May 1979|doi=10.1175/1520-0493(1979)107<0575:tbousi>2.0.co;2|bibcode = 1979MWRv..107..575R }}</ref>
{{clear}}

